ociety, and culture—changes that ultimately contributed as much to the character of today’s China as did the major battles. By analyzing the war as an international conflict, the author explains why so much of the present legitimacy of the Beijing government derives from its successes during the late 1940s, and reveals how the antagonism between China and the United States was born.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362009440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503620094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503620094/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles